user
I've addressed the round-0 findings. Summary of changes:
1. Split DooD wiring out of compose.subprocess.yaml into a new compose.docker-exec.yaml overlay layered ON TOP of subprocess.yaml. Plain subprocess (host) mode now has zero docker socket access. Both smoke scripts gained sanity assertions: smoke-subprocess.sh asserts the docker socket is NOT bound; smoke-subprocess-docker.sh asserts it IS bound. Updated docs accordingly.
2. Strengthened the git-mount integration test to model the real worktree-with-gitlink case: a bare repo at one mount target, a worktree whose .git is a gitlink file pointing into the bare repo, and the wrap mounts BOTH paths into the spawned child. Replaced the previous standalone-bind-mount test.
3. Added a new docker integration test that drives the actual SIGKILL escalation path through Subprocess.terminate(): trap-empty SIGTERM in the user command, immediate shutdown_deadline forces SIGKILL, asserts the spawned sibling container is gone via post_kill_callback (not just the local docker-run client). Also asserts the cleanup callback unlinked the cidfile.
4. Removed the cidfile-reap drift from the plan: cidfile paths are uuid-suffixed so reuse is impossible, and reap_orphaned_containers correctly does not touch cidfiles.

Please re-review the plan and implementation.
codex
Re-reviewing the updated surface against the previous findings first: I’m checking the new overlay split, the strengthened docker tests, and the plan/doc updates before I reassess ship readiness.
